The Telegraph - Calcutta : International
 Sunday, January 04, 2004 				 Saudi school reform threat
																								Riyadh, Jan. 3 (Reuters): Some 150 Saudis, including judges, university professors and a cleric with links to Muslim militants, have signed a document warning the kingdom against changing its Islam-based school curricula.																								The warning, which was obtained by Reuters today, was signed on January 1, a day after Saudi intellectuals, clerics and prominent personalities recommended educational reforms at the end of a conference held to tackle the roots of militancy.																								Saudi Arabia is battling a wave of attacks by suspected Islamist militants believed to be linked to Saudi-born Osama bin Ladens al Qaida. Suicide attacks have killed more than 50 people since May 2003.
